    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the students. I want to make sure they really get the 'why' behind it. Could you add a section that explains why this doctrine is considered such a vital instrument for justice in modern American society? Like, why is it seen as a necessary progress from just following simple procedures?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is a vital instrument for justice in modern American society because it recognizes that certain rights are so fundamental to our freedom and dignity that they should not be left to the whims of legislative or executive powers. This doctrine ensures that the government cannot infringe upon these rights, even if the procedures it follows are technically legal. It is a necessary progression from merely following procedures because it acknowledges that some rights are so essential to our well-being and autonomy that they must be protected from government interference, regardless of the process. This principle has been instrumental in advancing civil rights, such as the right to privacy and the right to marry, and has helped shape a more just and equitable society. By safeguarding these fundamental rights, substantive due process has played a crucial role in ensuring that the government respects and upholds the liberties that are central to our democratic way of life.",
      "source": "target",
